In TypeScript, you can handle cases where you have a theoretical type and a practical, known type by leveraging type aliases and type guards. Here's a way to achieve this:

### Using Type Aliases
You can define a type alias that represents the theoretical type, and then use this alias in your code where you know the practical type.

```typescript
// Theoretical type
type TheoreticalType = { value: number; };

// Practical type, which you know will only have this type
type PracticalType = TheoreticalType;

// Using the type alias
const value: PracticalType = 42;

// Checking the type using a type guard
if (PracticalType === value) {
  console.log("The value is of type PracticalType.");
} else {
  console.log("The value is of type TheoreticalType.");
}
```

### Using Type Guards
Type guards allow you to specify a type check condition. You can use a type guard to enforce that a value is of the practical type even if it theoretically could be another type.

```typescript
// Practical type, which you know will only have this type
type PracticalType = TheoreticalType;

// Using a type guard
const value: PracticalType = 42;

if (PracticalType === value) {
  console.log("The value is of type PracticalType.");
} else {
  console.log("The value is of type TheoreticalType.");
}
```

### Using Union Types
While TypeScript doesn't natively support type unions like some other languages, you can use conditional types or switch cases to handle different theoretical types in a more complex scenario.

```typescript
// Theoretical type
type TheoreticalType = { value: number; };

// Practical type, which you know will only have this type
type PracticalType = TheoreticalType;

// Conditional type
type TheoreticalUnion = TheoreticalType | number | string | undefined;

const value: TheoreticalUnion = 42;

if (value as TheoreticalUnion === TheoreticalType) {
  console.log("The value is of type TheoreticalType.");
} else if (value as number) {
  console.log("The value is a number.");
} else if (value as string) {
  console.log("The value is a string.");
} else {
  console.log("The value is undefined.");
}
```

### Summary
- **Type Aliases**: Define a theoretical type and use it in practical contexts.
- **Type Guards**: Use a type guard to enforce the practical type.
- **Union Types**: Use conditional types or unions to handle different theoretical types in more complex scenarios.

These approaches help you manage cases where you have a theoretical type and a practical type in TypeScript.

